rote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; An alternative to this, though, might be to never test for *ppos == 0 in<br />&gt; u32_array_read() and do the format_array_alloc() in u32_array_open() to<br />&gt; initialize file-&gt;private_data.  If that allocation fails, just return<br />&gt; -ENOMEM.  Then you never need to add a mutex in the read path.<br />&gt;<br />&gt; Any reason we can't do this?<br /><br />That does look simpler, and avoiding the lock is a good idea. Since we<br />don't support lseek() (or pread/pwrite) on that thing anyway, there's<br />no way to keep the fd open and just re-use it to read the data over<br />and over, so populating it at open time sounds like a good solution<br />with no real downsides.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
